The concept map structures Spatial Resolution into three primary dimensions: Pixel Density, Sampling Rate, and Application Requirements.

Pixel Density (measured in PPI/DPI) defines the physical grid layout of the matrix, directly influencing human detail perception and screen pitch.

The Sampling Rate represents the spatial frequency of capture, governed strictly by the foundational Nyquist Theorem established by Shannon (1949).

Violating the Nyquist limit creates data misalignments, which manifest as destructive aliasing and geometric artifacts in the digital output.

These sampling characteristics are physically driven by Sensor Properties, where pixel size, quantum efficiency, and noise levels set the baseline limits (Szeliski, 2010).

In parallel, the Optics System acts as a primary filter, where lens quality, aberrations, and the Modulation Transfer Function (MTF) determine resolving limits (Szeliski, 2010).

External Illumination Conditions modify the signal by controlling light intensity and contrast, enabling proper sensor activation (Gonzalez & Woods, 2018).

Downstream Processing & Compression algorithms enable image scaling but risk introducing structural compression artifacts (Gonzalez & Woods, 2018).

The rightmost branch highlights that resolution choices must match target Application Requirements, factoring in human eye limitations and viewing distance.

Ultimately, high-stakes tasks like medical or satellite imaging demand maximum resolution, whereas web applications scale down to prioritize storage and speed.
